<br>
X – You are letting your passions overload your argument, and you are letting some anonymous poster press your buttons.<br>
<br>
Okay, a few pertinent. I am certainly pro-second amendment. I believe that the second amendment guarantees the individuals right to keep and bear arms [two points: 1) At the time the Constitution was written Militias consisted of every male in an area. 2) If it guarantees only the governments right to arms then it is the only one of the first ten amendments (The Bill of Rights) to do so – the others all protect the individual from the Government. 3) I know I only listed two, but this one I cannot point directly too but I am sure others can. About 20 years after the Revolutionary War a group of men who had fought somewhere in New York were given state-of-the-art rifles for their services during the war. These men were no longer in the local militia]<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Okay, comments:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The Second amendment is an anachronism – the Founding Fathers couldn’t have envisioned modern weapons.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> True enough, but neither could they envision modern telecommunications – so should the government control broadcast news just because it wasn’t thought of 220+ years ago? Wait, the already do – never mind.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Gun crime is higher in countries with lax gun laws.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> No kidding? In countries with lax shovel laws there are more shovel related crimes. The true test is the overall crime rate per capita. Is the UK’s rate per capita lower than the US’s? I do know Australia – in the year immediately after they seized civilian guns their murder rate increased by almost nothing (probably because murder is a crime of passion and people will find a way). Their non-gun crime rate soared, increasing well over 5X the rate in the year proceeding the seizure.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
So much for free speech<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Displaying a lack of understanding. The first amendment protects against government censure – individuals are free to slam you if they wish. As a moderator I could shut down any argument I wished and not violate anyone’s first amendment right to free speech. Do not confuse protection against the government as a blanket right to make people listen to what you have to say.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Further, I neither claim psychic powers, or that you are a dick, though both may or may not be true - I don't know.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> X may be a dick. Believe it or not it is completely okay to be a dick, in fact it is Constitutionally protected.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Guns won't give you security<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The hell they wont! Guns are the ultimate equalizer, and like it or not they do provide security – why else would the police, military, and protective organizations (Secret Service, licensed bodyguards) use the?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
If you have a gun, you better be prepared to step over a line and know that you may have to use it.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I know that I could use one should the need arise. If you are not prepared to kill, then don’t get a gun. At the moment I don’t have a gun, but if I felt threatened I would buy one. If my life (or my families lives) were threatened I would kill. Perhaps you think I am evil for that, but I think someone who wouldn’t kill to protect themselves or their loved ones deserves what they get.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Final random thoughts:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The problem is not guns – guns are simply tools (frighteningly efficient tools). The problem is people. The US culture has a problem with violence, and removing guns will not solve that problem. <br>
<br>
In every case where a formally free nation fell to totalitarianism the seizure of guns was one of the first orders of business.<br>
<br>
Another though, “We the People” constitute the US government; thus even if the second amendment grants only the government the right to keep and bear arms then we as the government have that right, don’t we? Or do only the people we elect have the right to tell us who has the right? Right?<br>
 <br>
Democracy – One of my pet peeves. If you think you live in a Democracy then you are an abysmal fool. Democracies are dangerous. Most of us live in some form of Republic. I know people will say, “Well, Democratic Republic so calling it a Democracy is correct!” <br>
That is wrong. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
